Today, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, which were due to an improper treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overburdening of staff - all factors that are not directly attributing to the incidence of infections, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, the disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumaatology department of János Hospital, a MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The bacteria resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with a MRSA infection. An important operation had not yet been performed since due to the bacteria still in the patient’s body.
By 10 December this year, multiresistant pathogens had reported infections to the National Nosocomialis Monitoring System from hospitals in 1094, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemic Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multiresistant pathogens have been safely registered in hospitals, but the dark number may be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by the MRSA, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria carries about a third of the people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as neck inflammation, constipation, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well-healed.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or used improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotics-resistant which spread rapidly in the hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the hospital everyday.
One could not confuse the infection with the epidemic, said Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only doesn’t exist where it is not sought.
Resistance to antibiotics
“Such patients are isolated, the care staff wear rubber gloves and masks while providing, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
While the patients are being investigated for MRSA during their hospital delivery, infection cannot always be avoided.
Samples too rare
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the currently prevailing conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable for the prevention of the emergence or the spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-fashioned homes, the hospitals should examine the patients supplied and immediately isolate MRSA infected.
In the Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practiced as often.
Not least because there are no grants for this investigation on the part of the state health insurance company.
Therefore, most cases come to light only when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
From the European Union's side, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological investigations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can form, but this directive of hospitals is not always held.
Among the ambulances, or patients in the basic care, microbiological samples are even rarer, according to Karolina Böröcz.
In the case of disinfectants
Scientific evidence proves that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to another by care personnel.
That is why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there is also considerable weakness in the hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by drug infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient in the local hospitals.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds are barely arranged together, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz continues to note, unfortunately, in the financially less well-formed hospitals, it occurs that in disinfectants, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that directly favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are taken, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
