Fodor and the Six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries advise on the Bali timetable in which the emissions-reducing measures are set for the period following 2012, i.e. after the execution of the Kyoto Protocol.
At present, there is a fierce debate between industrial and developing countries.
The United States has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate on concrete numbers, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether industrial states are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on the support of developing countries has also been reached.
The adjustment fund provided for by the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected to be read out at the UN Global Environmental Facility (GEF), as in the Piac és Profit.
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, in the name of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection measures, and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister declared that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether or not the “renewal after 2012” will be successful. The Union would be willing to make a 30-percent reduction, provided other major industrial states of the world, or developing countries are also willing to meet their obligations according to forces and responsibilities.
Gábor Fodor emphasized that the objective of the states that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU had already committed to 8% with its 15 member states at the time.
The requirement for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the years 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will fully meet as set out in the Environmental Ministry press release.
In this case, the long-term international climate policy agreement will not follow a new, international emission reduction system, the IPCC, the international Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee of the UN in its latest report.
As a result, emissions reduction would slow down, and the increase in Earth’s average temperature by more than 2° C. would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
